{"title_page": "Yevgeny Nikonov", "text_new": "[[File:Yevgeny_Nikonov.jpg|thumb|right]]\n'''Yevgeny Alexandrovich Nikonov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u0301\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041d\u0438\u0301\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432}}; 18 December 1920 \u2013 19 August 1941, in [[Harku]], [[Estonia]]) was a Russian sailor during the Soviet defense of Estonia in 1941. He is a holder of the [[Hero of the Soviet Union]], the Soviet Union's highest award.\n\n==Life and death==\nNikonov was born on 18 December 1920 into an ethnically Russian peasant family in the village of [[Vasilyevka, Stavropolsky District, Samara Oblast|Vasilyevka]] in what is now [[Stavropolsky District]] of [[Samara Oblast]].{{efn|name=Stavropol Region}} He joined the navy in 1939 and served as a torpedo electrician on the [[destroyer leader]] [[Leningrad-class destroyer|''Minsk'']] attached to the Soviet [[Baltic Fleet]].\n\nFollowing the 1941 German [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of the Soviet Union]], Nikonov and many other Baltic Fleet sailors were deployed as emergency [[Naval Infantry (Russia)|naval infantry]].\n\nNikonov fought in the defense of [[Tallinn]] (5\u201328 August 1941), the main base of the Baltic Fleet. While engaged in reconnaissance near the town of [[Keila]] on 19 August he was seriously wounded and captured. Despite being tortured, Nikonov refused to give his captors any military information, for which the Germans doused him with gasoline and burned him alive.\n\nOn 19 April 1943 Baltic Fleet commander Vice\u2013Admiral [[Vladimir Tributs]] ordered that Torpedo Electrician Yevgeny Nikonov forever be listed as a member of the ''Minsk'''s active crew. (This tradition continues today; although the ''Minsk'' was long ago scrapped, Yevgeny Nikonov is always listed on the active personnel roster of a Baltic Fleet training unit.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltflot.vif20.ru/moriaki_geroi.html|title=\u041c\u043e\u0440\u044f\u043a\u0438-\u0431\u0430\u043b\u0442\u0438\u0439\u0446\u044b, \u0437\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0447\u043d\u043e \u0432 \u0441\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0438 \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0439 \u0434\u0432\u0430\u0436\u0434\u044b \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0411\u0430\u043b\u0442\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0430|trans-title=Baltic Fleet sailors, entered forever onto the lists of ships and twice part of the Red Banner Baltic Fleet|author=Anna Ivanova|date=|work=The Baltic Fleet|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nNikonov was posthumously awarded the title of Hero of the Soviet Union on 3 September 1957.\n\n==Controversy==\nThere is no documented proof of whether the story behind Nikonov's death was true. The whole story may be based on a propaganda leaflet drawn by Viktor Ivanov and Olga Burova, which depicted a sailor from a boat ''Minsk'' being burned by the Germans <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.domznaniy74.ru/pics/uploads/Aktual_tema/Plakat%20WOW/6_Lydi_mira/015_1942_Zapomni%20i%20otomsty_V.Ivanov_O.Burova.jpg|title=\u041b\u044e\u0434\u0438 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430, \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0443 \u0432\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u044c\u0442\u0435!|trans-title=People of the World, Stand up for a Minute!|author=|date=|work=\u0423\u0440\u0430\u043b\u043e-\u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0414\u043e\u043c \u0417\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439|accessdate= December 14, 2018}}</ref>. In 1943, the leaflet reached a wounded [[Political commissar#Soviet Union and the Eastern Bloc|commissar]], Grigori Shevchenko, who claimed that the drawing depicted a sailor called Yevgeny Nikonov, whom he knew. Also, on the alleged day of the burning of Yevgeny Nikonov (August 19, 1941), the Germans were not yet in Keila, and the battle for Tallinn started only on the next day. It is also alleged that that a former sailor using the name Yevgeny Nikonov has visited the burial site of Yevgeny Nikonov at Maarjam\u00e4e sometime in the 1980s, and also later the new burial site in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arvamus.postimees.ee/6198643/ander-asberg-punamadruse-kangelasloo-moistatus|title=Ander Asberg: punamadruse kangelasloo m\u00f5istatus|trans-title=Ander Asberg: the Enigma of Heroic Story of a Red Sailor|author=Andre Asberg|date=September 1, 2018|work=Postimees|accessdate= December 10, 2018}}</ref> The story of the heroic death of Nikonov was first published in the newsletter of the Red Baltic Fleet on March 26, 1943 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://vivaldi.nlr.ru/pn000149958/view#page=3|title=\u041c\u043e\u0440\u044f\u043a \u0441 \"\u041c\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\"|trans-title=A Sailor from \"Minsk\"|author=\u041b\u0435\u0439\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0442 \u0411\u043e\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e(lt Bondarenko)|date=March 26, 1943|work=\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0411\u0430\u043b\u0442\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442|accessdate=December 17, 2018}}</ref>. The information about the death of Nikonov appeared in the database of casualties only on April 24, 1943, that is after the story of the heroic death had already been published. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://obd-memorial.ru/html/info.htm?id=76178601|title=\u0418\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0438\u0437 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0438 ID:76178601|trans-title=information from the database ID:76178601|author=Data Bank \"Memorial\"|date=|work=|accessdate= December 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Burials==\n[[File:Demolished Monument of Evgeni Nikonov in Tallinn.jpg|thumb|left|Monument to Nikonov in Tallin (now demolished)]]\nNikonov was originally buried on a farm in [[Harku]]. On 19 March 1951 the Tallinn City Council decided to rename a street in Nikonov's honor. The same decree granted a request by Baltic Fleet Command for land in the [[Kadriorg]] district to construct a monument to Nikonov.\n\nSoon after, Nikonov's remains were ceremoniously reinterred in a picturesque location in Tallinn park, on the hill of Terra Mariana{{cn|date=May 2011}}, and a monument was erected. Following the collapse of the Soviet Union, the monument was demolished. (The statue, now missing its head, is at the outdoor exhibition of Soviet monuments at Maarjam\u00e4e Palace of the Estonian History Museum.) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajaloomuuseum.ee/visiting/buildings/maarjamae-palace|title=Eesti Ajaloomuuseum|trans-title=Estonian History Museum|author=|date=|work=|accessdate= December 10, 2018}}</ref>   \n\nOn 2 March 1992 Nikonov was again reinterred, in his home town of Vasilyevka in Russia. According to some sources, when the attempt was made to disinter Nikonov's remains for reburial in Russia, his remains were missing&nbsp;\u2013 it remains unclear, whether the remains were there in the first place. There have been accusations that the remains  were taken by Estonian nationalists, and were then offered in exchange for information about the burial location of some men of the [[20th Waffen Grenadier Division of the SS (1st Estonian)]] (a unit of Estonians who had fought for the Germans against the Soviets) who had been shot after the Soviets reoccupied Tallinn in 1944. So the reburial delegation from [[Tolyatti]] just filled the coffin with some earth from around Nikonov's grave and returned with that to Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.relga.ru/Environ/WebObjects/tgu-www.woa/wa/Main?searchPattern=\u0422\u043e\u043b\u044c\u044f\u0442\u0442\u0438&textid=343&level1=main&level2=articles|title=\u041d\u043e\u0448\u0430 \u0431\u0435\u0441\u0441\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f|trans-title=The burden of immortality|author=Sergei Melnik|date=March 29, 2005|work=Relga|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Memorialization==\n[[File:Monument of Evgeny Nikonov, Togliatty, Russia.JPG|thumb|Monument to Yevgeny Nikonov, Nikonov Square, Tolyatti. (V. I. Zhokov and I. K. Timofeev, architects; L. S. Martynov, sculptor)]]\n\n[[Tolyatti]], the city nearest Nikonov's birthplace, contains several memorials to him. A street was named in his honor on 13 November 1958, and a square in 1980. There is a memorial at school number 19 (now Lyceum \u2116 19). He is depicted on one of the faces of the [[Obelisk of Glory (Tolyatti)|Obelisk of Glory]] in Liberty Square. A memorial was opened on 9 May 1979 in Nikonov Square in the Gateway District.\n\nA tanker (of the shipping company Volgotanker) was named for Nikonov. A street and a school (school number 68, where Nikonov had studied) in the Moskovsky District of [[Nizhny Novgorod]] were named for Nikonov in 1957. Later, a monument was erected in front of the school, and in 1972 the school opened a museum of the hero. There is a memorial plaque at the plant where Nikonov worked, and a monument at his grave in the village of Vasilyevka. A street in the [[Krasnoglinsky City District|Krasnoglinsky District]] of [[Samara, Russia|Samara]] was named Hero Of The Soviet Union Nikonov Street on 5 January 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edc.samara.ru/~pobeda60/sites/162-2/Stranicu/nikonov.html |title=\u0423\u041b\u0418\u0426\u0410 \u0415\u0412\u0413\u0415\u041d\u0418\u042f \u041d\u0418\u041a\u041e\u041d\u041e\u0412\u0410 |trans-title=Yevgeniya Nikonova Street |author=School \u2116 162 Class 10 \"A\" |date= |publisher=Municipal Educational Institute, City of Samara  |accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Hero of the Soviet Union]]\n*[[Order of Lenin]]\n*[[Order of the Patriotic War]] First Class\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes\n| notes =\n\n{{efn\n| name = Stavropol Region\n| Stavropol District is not to be confused with [[Stavropol Region]]. Stavropol District was formed in 1928. Samara Oblast was named Kuybyshev Oblast from 1935 to 1990.\n}}\n\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://citytlt.narod.ru/lichheronikonov.htm Biography at Tolyatti history website] {{in lang|ru}}\n*[http://www.relga.ru/Environ/WebObjects/tgu-www.woa/wa/Main?searchPattern=\u0422\u043e\u043b\u044c\u044f\u0442\u0442\u0438&textid=343&level1=main&level2=articles Yevgeny Nikonov article at Relga] {{in lang|ru}}\n*[http://gorod63.ru/gallery/slide/monument/&n_6/ Nikonov Monument at Virtual Tolyatti] {{in lang|ru}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nikonov, Yevgeny}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:Executed people from Samara Oblast]]\n[[Category:Soviet Navy personnel]]\n[[Category:Electricians]]\n[[Category:Russian people executed by Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Soviet military personnel killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:Executed Soviet people from Russia]]\n[[Category:Russian torture victims]]\n[[Category:Executed Russian people]]\n[[Category:People executed by Estonia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Patriotic War, 1st class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Lenin]]\n[[Category:Heroes of the Soviet Union]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Yevgeny_Nikonov.jpg|thumb|right]]\n'''Yevgeny Alexandrovich Nikonov''' ({{lang-ru|\u0415\u0432\u0433\u0435\u0301\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u0301\u043d\u0434\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u041d\u0438\u0301\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u0432}}; 18 December 1920 \u2013 19 August 1941, in [[Harku]], [[Estonia]]) was a Russian sailor during the Soviet defense of Estonia in 1941. He is a holder of the [[Hero of the Soviet Union]], the Soviet Union's highest award.\n\n==Life and death==\nNikonov was born on 18 December 1920 into an ethnically Russian peasant family in the village of [[Vasilyevka, Stavropolsky District, Samara Oblast|Vasilyevka]] in what is now [[Stavropolsky District]] of [[Samara Oblast]].{{efn|name=Stavropol Region}} He joined the navy in 1939 and served as a torpedo electrician on the [[destroyer leader]] [[Leningrad-class destroyer|''Minsk'']] attached to the Soviet [[Baltic Fleet]].\n\nFollowing the 1941 German [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of the Soviet Union]], Nikonov and many other Baltic Fleet sailors were deployed as emergency [[Naval Infantry (Russia)|naval infantry]].\n\nNikonov fought in the defense of [[Tallinn]] (5\u201328 August 1941), the main base of the Baltic Fleet. While engaged in reconnaissance near the town of [[Keila]] on 19 August he was seriously wounded and captured. Despite being tortured, Nikonov refused to give his captors any military information, for which the Germans doused him with gasoline and burned him alive.\n\nOn 19 April 1943 Baltic Fleet commander Vice\u2013Admiral [[Vladimir Tributs]] ordered that Torpedo Electrician Yevgeny Nikonov forever be listed as a member of the ''Minsk'''s active crew. (This tradition continues today; although the ''Minsk'' was long ago scrapped, Yevgeny Nikonov is always listed on the active personnel roster of a Baltic Fleet training unit.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://baltflot.vif20.ru/moriaki_geroi.html|title=\u041c\u043e\u0440\u044f\u043a\u0438-\u0431\u0430\u043b\u0442\u0438\u0439\u0446\u044b, \u0437\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0432\u0435\u0447\u043d\u043e \u0432 \u0441\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0435\u0439 \u0438 \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0439 \u0434\u0432\u0430\u0436\u0434\u044b \u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0411\u0430\u043b\u0442\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442\u0430|trans-title=Baltic Fleet sailors, entered forever onto the lists of ships and twice part of the Red Banner Baltic Fleet|author=Anna Ivanova|date=|work=The Baltic Fleet|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\nNikonov was posthumously awarded the title of Hero of the Soviet Union on 3 September 1957.\n\n==Controversy==\nThere is no documented proof of whether the story behind Nikonov's death was truw. The whole story may be based on a propaganda leaflet drawn by Viktor Ivanov and Olga Burova, which depicted a sailor from a boat ''Minsk'' being burned by the Germans <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.domznaniy74.ru/pics/uploads/Aktual_tema/Plakat%20WOW/6_Lydi_mira/015_1942_Zapomni%20i%20otomsty_V.Ivanov_O.Burova.jpg|title=\u041b\u044e\u0434\u0438 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430, \u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0443 \u0432\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u044c\u0442\u0435!|trans-title=People of the World, Stand up for a Minute!|author=|date=|work=\u0423\u0440\u0430\u043b\u043e-\u0421\u0438\u0431\u0438\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0414\u043e\u043c \u0417\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439|accessdate= December 14, 2018}}</ref>. In 1943, the leaflet reached a wounded [[Political commissar#Soviet Union and the Eastern Bloc|commissar]], Grigori Shevchenko, who claimed that the drawing depicted a sailor called Yevgeny Nikonov, whom he knew. Also, on the alleged day of the burning of Yevgeny Nikonov (August 19, 1941), the Germans were not yet in Keila, and the battle for Tallinn started only on the next day. It is also alleged that that a former sailor using the name Yevgeny Nikonov has visited the burial site of Yevgeny Nikonov at Maarjam\u00e4e sometime in the 1980s, and also later the new burial site in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arvamus.postimees.ee/6198643/ander-asberg-punamadruse-kangelasloo-moistatus|title=Ander Asberg: punamadruse kangelasloo m\u00f5istatus|trans-title=Ander Asberg: the Enigma of Heroic Story of a Red Sailor|author=Andre Asberg|date=September 1, 2018|work=Postimees|accessdate= December 10, 2018}}</ref> The story of the heroic death of Nikonov was first published in the newsletter of the Red Baltic Fleet on March 26, 1943 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://vivaldi.nlr.ru/pn000149958/view#page=3|title=\u041c\u043e\u0440\u044f\u043a \u0441 \"\u041c\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0430\"|trans-title=A Sailor from \"Minsk\"|author=\u041b\u0435\u0439\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0430\u043d\u0442 \u0411\u043e\u043d\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e(lt Bondarenko)|date=March 26, 1943|work=\u041a\u0440\u0430\u0441\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0411\u0430\u043b\u0442\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0444\u043b\u043e\u0442|accessdate=December 17, 2018}}</ref>. The information about the death of Nikonov appeared in the database of casualties only on April 24, 1943, that is after the story of the heroic death had already been published. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://obd-memorial.ru/html/info.htm?id=76178601|title=\u0418\u043d\u0444\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0438\u0437 \u043a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0442\u0435\u043a\u0438 ID:76178601|trans-title=information from the database ID:76178601|author=Data Bank \"Memorial\"|date=|work=|accessdate= December 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Burials==\n[[File:Demolished Monument of Evgeni Nikonov in Tallinn.jpg|thumb|left|Monument to Nikonov in Tallin (now demolished)]]\nNikonov was originally buried on a farm in [[Harku]]. On 19 March 1951 the Tallinn City Council decided to rename a street in Nikonov's honor. The same decree granted a request by Baltic Fleet Command for land in the [[Kadriorg]] district to construct a monument to Nikonov.\n\nSoon after, Nikonov's remains were ceremoniously reinterred in a picturesque location in Tallinn park, on the hill of Terra Mariana{{cn|date=May 2011}}, and a monument was erected. Following the collapse of the Soviet Union, the monument was demolished. (The statue, now missing its head, is at the outdoor exhibition of Soviet monuments at Maarjam\u00e4e Palace of the Estonian History Museum.) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajaloomuuseum.ee/visiting/buildings/maarjamae-palace|title=Eesti Ajaloomuuseum|trans-title=Estonian History Museum|author=|date=|work=|accessdate= December 10, 2018}}</ref>   \n\nOn 2 March 1992 Nikonov was again reinterred, in his home town of Vasilyevka in Russia. According to some sources, when the attempt was made to disinter Nikonov's remains for reburial in Russia, his remains were missing&nbsp;\u2013 it remains unclear, whether the remains were there in the first place. There have been accusations that the remains  were taken by Estonian nationalists, and were then offered in exchange for information about the burial location of some men of the [[20th Waffen Grenadier Division of the SS (1st Estonian)]] (a unit of Estonians who had fought for the Germans against the Soviets) who had been shot after the Soviets reoccupied Tallinn in 1944. So the reburial delegation from [[Tolyatti]] just filled the coffin with some earth from around Nikonov's grave and returned with that to Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.relga.ru/Environ/WebObjects/tgu-www.woa/wa/Main?searchPattern=\u0422\u043e\u043b\u044c\u044f\u0442\u0442\u0438&textid=343&level1=main&level2=articles|title=\u041d\u043e\u0448\u0430 \u0431\u0435\u0441\u0441\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438\u044f|trans-title=The burden of immortality|author=Sergei Melnik|date=March 29, 2005|work=Relga|accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Memorialization==\n[[File:Monument of Evgeny Nikonov, Togliatty, Russia.JPG|thumb|Monument to Yevgeny Nikonov, Nikonov Square, Tolyatti. (V. I. Zhokov and I. K. Timofeev, architects; L. S. Martynov, sculptor)]]\n\n[[Tolyatti]], the city nearest Nikonov's birthplace, contains several memorials to him. A street was named in his honor on 13 November 1958, and a square in 1980. There is a memorial at school number 19 (now Lyceum \u2116 19). He is depicted on one of the faces of the [[Obelisk of Glory (Tolyatti)|Obelisk of Glory]] in Liberty Square. A memorial was opened on 9 May 1979 in Nikonov Square in the Gateway District.\n\nA tanker (of the shipping company Volgotanker) was named for Nikonov. A street and a school (school number 68, where Nikonov had studied) in the Moskovsky District of [[Nizhny Novgorod]] were named for Nikonov in 1957. Later, a monument was erected in front of the school, and in 1972 the school opened a museum of the hero. There is a memorial plaque at the plant where Nikonov worked, and a monument at his grave in the village of Vasilyevka. A street in the [[Krasnoglinsky City District|Krasnoglinsky District]] of [[Samara, Russia|Samara]] was named Hero Of The Soviet Union Nikonov Street on 5 January 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edc.samara.ru/~pobeda60/sites/162-2/Stranicu/nikonov.html |title=\u0423\u041b\u0418\u0426\u0410 \u0415\u0412\u0413\u0415\u041d\u0418\u042f \u041d\u0418\u041a\u041e\u041d\u041e\u0412\u0410 |trans-title=Yevgeniya Nikonova Street |author=School \u2116 162 Class 10 \"A\" |date= |publisher=Municipal Educational Institute, City of Samara  |accessdate=April 13, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Hero of the Soviet Union]]\n*[[Order of Lenin]]\n*[[Order of the Patriotic War]] First Class\n\n==Notes==\n{{notes\n| notes =\n\n{{efn\n| name = Stavropol Region\n| Stavropol District is not to be confused with [[Stavropol Region]]. Stavropol District was formed in 1928. Samara Oblast was named Kuybyshev Oblast from 1935 to 1990.\n}}\n\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://citytlt.narod.ru/lichheronikonov.htm Biography at Tolyatti history website] {{in lang|ru}}\n*[http://www.relga.ru/Environ/WebObjects/tgu-www.woa/wa/Main?searchPattern=\u0422\u043e\u043b\u044c\u044f\u0442\u0442\u0438&textid=343&level1=main&level2=articles Yevgeny Nikonov article at Relga] {{in lang|ru}}\n*[http://gorod63.ru/gallery/slide/monument/&n_6/ Nikonov Monument at Virtual Tolyatti] {{in lang|ru}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nikonov, Yevgeny}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1941 deaths]]\n[[Category:Executed people from Samara Oblast]]\n[[Category:Soviet Navy personnel]]\n[[Category:Electricians]]\n[[Category:Russian people executed by Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Soviet military personnel killed in World War II]]\n[[Category:Executed Soviet people from Russia]]\n[[Category:Russian torture victims]]\n[[Category:Executed Russian people]]\n[[Category:People executed by Estonia]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Patriotic War, 1st class]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Lenin]]\n[[Category:Heroes of the Soviet Union]]\n", "name_user": "Mandsford", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eControversy", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yevgeny_Nikonov"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Singapore}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore\n<!--Difficult to update, so no longer appropriate\n| map2            = COVID-19 Cases in Singapore by Planning Areas.svg\n| legend2         = {{center|Map of planning areas with confirmed (red) coronavirus cases (as of 11 March)}}\n-->\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Singapore]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 23 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=23|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 297<ref name=\"worldometers\">[https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/ worldometers.info]</ref><ref name=\"DashBoard\"/><ref name=\"CTSG\"/>\n| deaths          = 6<ref name=\"worldometers\"/><ref name=\"DashBoard\">[https://coronaboard.com COVID-19 Dashboard]</ref><ref name=\"CTSG\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 1,189<ref name=\"worldometers\"/><ref name=\"DashBoard\"/><ref name=\"CTSG\">[https://www.coronatracker.com/country/sg Corona Tracker Overview]</ref>\n| active          = \n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://www.moh.gov.sg/covid-19}}\n| First Case detected: = \n}}\nThe '''2020 coronavirus pandemic in Singapore''' is part of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic|ongoing global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19), a novel infectious disease caused by [[severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2]] (SARS-CoV-2). The first case of COVID-19 was confirmed on 23 January 2020.<ref name=\"Abdullah 2020\" /> To combat COVID-19, a multi-ministerial committee was formed on 22 January with Minister for National Development [[Lawrence Wong]] and Minister for Health [[Gan Kim Yong]] as the co-chairs and [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]] [[Lee Hsien Loong]] and [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore|Deputy Prime Minister]] and Minister for Finance [[Heng Swee Keat]] as advisors.<ref name=\"ST22Jan\"/><ref>https://www.moh.gov.sg/docs/librariesprovider5/default-document-library/multi-ministry-taskforce-on-wuhan-coronavirus-and-tor---final.pdf</ref>\n\nOn 3 April 2020, Singapore announced a stringent set of preventive measures which was collectively called a 'circuit breaker'.\n[[Singapore]] contributed US$500,000 to support [[WHO]] efforts against COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Singapore contributes US$500,000 to support WHO efforts against COVID-19 |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/singapore-contributes-s-500-000-to-support-who-covid-19-efforts-12568566 |accessdate=25 March 2020 |work=CNA |language=en}}</ref>\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Singapore medical cases chart}}\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe top plot shows the total number of cases as a function of time (by date) since 23 January 2020, the date of the first reported case in Singapore. The bottom plot shows the number of new cases as reported each day.\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|colors=orange, blue, red\n| legend=Legend\n| width = 900\n| height = 350\n| xAxisTitle = Date (day/month)\n| yAxisTitle = Total no. of cases (cumulative)\n| y1Title=Confirmed\n| y2Title=Recovered\n| y3Title=Deaths\n| xAxisAngle = -65\n| yGrid= |xGrid= \n| x =  23/1, 24/1, 25/1, 26/1, 27/1, 28/1, 29/1, 30/1, 31/1, 1/2, 2/2, 3/2, 4/2, 5/2, 6/2, 7/2, 8/2, 9/2, 10/2, 11/2, 12/2, 13/2, 14/2, 15/2, 16/2, 17/2, 18/2, 19/2, 20/2, 21/2, 22/2, 23/2, 24/2, 25/2, 26/2, 27/2, 28/2, 29/2, 1/3, 2/3, 3/3, 4/3, 5/3, 6/3, 7/3, 8/3, 9/3, 10/3, 11/3, 12/3, 13/3, 14/3, 15/3, 16/3, 17/3, 18/3, 19/3, 20/3, 21/3, 22/3, 23/3, 24/3, 25/3, 26/3, 27/3, 28/3, 29